WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.850 --> 00:00:08.630
&gt;&gt; Male presenter: Welcome to Authors at Google
at Cambridge, Massachusetts.

00:00:08.630 --> 00:00:12.790
Today we welcome author Larry Tye, who will
discuss this latest book Superman: The High

00:00:12.790 --> 00:00:17.449
Flying History of America's Most Enduring
Hero.

00:00:17.449 --> 00:00:22.380
Larry runs the Boston based Health Coverage
Fellowship which is designed to help the media

00:00:22.380 --> 00:00:25.280
do a better job covering critical health care
issues.

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:31.920
Each year it trains ten medical journalists
and newspapers, radio stations and TV outlets

00:00:31.920 --> 00:00:33.350
from across the country.

00:00:33.350 --> 00:00:34.890
On topics ranging from public health and mental
health to insuring the uninsured.

00:00:34.890 --> 00:00:43.390
From 1986 to 2001, Larry was a beat reporter
with the Boston Globe where his primary beat

00:00:43.390 --> 00:00:44.489
was medicine.

00:00:44.489 --> 00:00:51.729
He also served at the Globe's environmental
reporter, roving national writer, investigative

00:00:51.729 --> 00:00:52.889
reporter and sports writer.

00:00:52.889 --> 00:00:57.190
And if you look at the Boston Globe archives
you'll see that his byline appeared on over

00:00:57.190 --> 00:01:03.730
7,000 articles over 15 years, so I think he
probably doesn't have trouble disciplining

00:01:03.730 --> 00:01:05.960
himself to research and writing.

00:01:05.960 --> 00:01:10.590
He's the author of five previous books, including
the 2009 New York Times bestseller Satchel:

00:01:10.590 --> 00:01:14.740
The Life and Times [clears throat] of an American
Legend.

00:01:14.740 --> 00:01:22.340
Which is a biography of two American icons,
the great baseball pitcher Satchel Page, and

00:01:22.340 --> 00:01:32.909
Jim Crow, who was the characterization, personification
of the amalgam of racial laws in the south

00:01:32.909 --> 00:01:38.299
that mandated the separation of races in all
public spaces.

00:01:38.299 --> 00:01:42.100
Without further ado, please give a warm welcome
to Larry Tye.

00:01:42.100 --> 00:01:45.000
[Applause]
&gt;&gt; Larry: So other than the camera back there

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:46.000
we should make this really informal.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:51.630
Small group, we can make this intimate and
the, and I want to tell you a little bit about

00:01:51.630 --> 00:01:58.640
what I, why I wrote a book about Superman
and what I found and then we can talk about

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:01.159
it, or we can go enjoy a beautiful day or
do whatever you like.

00:02:01.159 --> 00:02:06.689
So where I want to actually start out is saying,
I don't know how much of you know what happens

00:02:06.689 --> 00:02:07.890
when you kick off a book.

00:02:07.890 --> 00:02:14.650
When you always dream about something big
happening that the, that will lend an event

00:02:14.650 --> 00:02:19.220
and some publicity and some oomph to getting
started with a book.

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:25.480
And the, I went to a very strange place, has
anybody ever heard of a town called Metropolis?

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:28.970
There really is a Metropolis.

00:02:28.970 --> 00:02:31.240
Anybody know where Metropolis is?

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:32.600
It's in Illinois?

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:34.480
Anybody ever hear, nobody's ever heard of
Metropolis, Illinois.

00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:41.320
Well, it's a place so obscure and so unlike
the real Metropolis that we see in the comic

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:47.940
books that to get there from Boston, what
you have to do is take a plane to O'Hare and

00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:53.450
then take one of two planes everyday that
are like puddle jumpers that go from O'Hare

00:02:53.450 --> 00:02:54.450
airport to Paducah, Kentucky.

00:02:54.450 --> 00:03:00.060
And then when you get to Paducah, Kentucky
you have to hope that somebody is there that

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:05.220
will take you the 13 miles across the Ohio
River to the part of Illinois that is more

00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:08.730
like the south than anything else in Illinois.

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:13.780
And the, I ended up there, so this is a town
you can get into and you see that not only

00:03:13.780 --> 00:03:18.490
doesn't it have an airport or a train station,
it doesn't have a taxi cab or a rental car

00:03:18.490 --> 00:03:22.560
company or anything that would give a sense
that it was really a metropolis.

00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:26.940
What it has is a big sign saying it is the
official home of Superman.

00:03:26.940 --> 00:03:31.690
[Laughter] And it has, on most weekends, when
you get there about 5,000 people.

00:03:31.690 --> 00:03:36.710
On the weekend that I went there, the reason
it was the perfect place to kick off my book

00:03:36.710 --> 00:03:42.130
was not just because it declares itself the
official home of Superman, but because every

00:03:42.130 --> 00:03:49.060
summer, in June, it, that happened to coincide
with the actual weekend my book planned to

00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:50.060
come out.

00:03:50.060 --> 00:03:56.350
It is the home to the Superman festival, with
30,000 people come from across the world to

00:03:56.350 --> 00:03:57.970
celebrate Superman.

00:03:57.970 --> 00:03:59.900
So it's like your dream kickoff party.

00:03:59.900 --> 00:04:05.300
30,000 [Laughter] of Superman's best friends
from everywhere are there along with all the

00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:09.220
crazy press that cares about comic books and
particularly Superman.

00:04:09.220 --> 00:04:14.920
And so I went there and I want to just tell
you about one thing that happened to me when

00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:15.920
I was there.

00:04:15.920 --> 00:04:19.669
I was in a hall, about to give, be a part
of a panel giving a big talk.

00:04:19.669 --> 00:04:24.020
And the, it was the biggest hall they had
in Metropolis, which probably seated 300 people.

00:04:24.020 --> 00:04:28.140
It was, I guess, a converted, some kind of
theater.

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:33.810
And this hall was about a third full and I'm
there on the panel with two guys who have

00:04:33.810 --> 00:04:36.720
played Superboy on TV series.

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:39.690
And we were enough of a draw to fill up a
third of a room.

00:04:39.690 --> 00:04:45.690
We get five minutes into our talk and suddenly
this guy walks into the room, a white haired

00:04:45.690 --> 00:04:52.940
guy with an ancient white haired lady on his
arm, looking like, if he'd let go of her,

00:04:52.940 --> 00:04:54.900
she might tumble down.

00:04:54.900 --> 00:04:59.620
And she goes and takes a seat up front but
doesn't say a word.

00:04:59.620 --> 00:05:05.260
And within about five minutes between text
messages and cell phone calls, the hall that

00:05:05.260 --> 00:05:11.160
was a third full became overflowing and it
was overflowing because this was the woman,

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:13.440
anybody ever hear of somebody named Noel Neill?

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:14.440
&gt;&gt; Male presenter: Yeah.

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:15.560
&gt;&gt; Larry: Who was Noel Neill?

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:17.860
&gt;&gt; Male presenter: She played Lois Lane in
the '50s TV series.

00:05:17.860 --> 00:05:18.860
&gt;&gt; Larry: She did.

00:05:18.860 --> 00:05:22.350
For all but one year, for all but the first
year in the TV series she was Lois Lane.

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:28.389
There was something even worse in terms of
production value before the TV series there

00:05:28.389 --> 00:05:32.270
were, you're all much too young to remember
something called the movie serials.

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:37.080
But the movie serials were these shorts that
lasted 15 minutes.

00:05:37.080 --> 00:05:42.680
And on a Saturday afternoon most of America,
every kid in America, wanted to go to the

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:43.680
movies.

00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:46.980
And their parents thought they were going
to the movies to see Pride and Prejudice.

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:52.010
They were really going there to see the 15
minute Superman serial that preceded Pride

00:05:52.010 --> 00:05:53.270
and Prejudice.

00:05:53.270 --> 00:05:54.560
And these were terrible things.

00:05:54.560 --> 00:05:57.620
If you've ever heard of the expression cliff
hanger?

00:05:57.620 --> 00:06:02.560
Well, a cliffhanger came from these movie
serials because at the end of every serial,

00:06:02.560 --> 00:06:06.470
the heroine would be on a railroad track with
the train about to run her over.

00:06:06.470 --> 00:06:10.060
[Laughter] And it would end with the train
coming right to her.

00:06:10.060 --> 00:06:14.590
And it was a cliffhanger because it wanted
you to come back the next week for the next

00:06:14.590 --> 00:06:17.800
episode for a dozen episodes in the serial.

00:06:17.800 --> 00:06:22.071
And the best of all the serials was Superman
and Noel Niell was there.

00:06:22.071 --> 00:06:26.190
There were two people who made my day in Metropolis.

00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:33.590
One was Noel Niell and the other one was,
I brought you a little picture to show you

00:06:33.590 --> 00:06:41.230
who my other favorite guy there was in Metropolis.

00:06:41.230 --> 00:06:44.450
And that's me and that is the biggest Superman
in the world.

00:06:44.450 --> 00:06:50.050
[Laughter] 15 feet high and it is made of
bronze and this, I don't know if anybody reads

00:06:50.050 --> 00:06:52.210
ever the Boston Globe, but this picture, this
crazy picture was in the Globe travel section,

00:06:52.210 --> 00:06:58.900
me describing in the Sunday's Globe, in yesterday's
Globe, my trip to Metropolis.

00:06:58.900 --> 00:07:05.080
And he is made of bronze for one reason, he
was initially, Metropolis decided in it's

00:07:05.080 --> 00:07:09.870
three block long downtown that the only thing
the official home of Superman could have,

00:07:09.870 --> 00:07:14.700
it had to have a big statue of Superman looking
down the street towards downtown.

00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:19.199
The problem with the original statue was that
he was made of fiberglass.

00:07:19.199 --> 00:07:23.449
Now these are people in a town that is very
southern.

00:07:23.449 --> 00:07:28.389
And when Superman is made of fiberglass everybody
in town who has a gun --which was everybody

00:07:28.389 --> 00:07:31.320
in town-- had to see whether Superman was
in fact bulletproof.

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:35.580
[laughter] And it turned out the fiberglass
Superman was not bullet proof.

00:07:35.580 --> 00:07:41.510
So that became a bulletproof riddled statue
of Superman and this is what we got instead.

00:07:41.510 --> 00:07:46.530
And this statue has got many attempts to shoot
at him but he is made of bronze and it just

00:07:46.530 --> 00:07:49.150
bounces right off like it's supposed to.

00:07:49.150 --> 00:07:52.390
If you ever saw the original TV Superman series.

00:07:52.390 --> 00:07:57.020
Did you, anybody ever watch reruns that black
and white TV series?

00:07:57.020 --> 00:07:59.449
There's something very strange that goes on
there.

00:07:59.449 --> 00:08:04.270
And what is strange is Superman is bullet
proof and you watch people shooting at him

00:08:04.270 --> 00:08:05.890
and the bullets bounce off.

00:08:05.890 --> 00:08:10.860
But when they get frustrated they throw their
gun at him and he ducks.

00:08:10.860 --> 00:08:13.900
[laughter] [inaudible] Superman.

00:08:13.900 --> 00:08:19.770
So what I want to do is take you for a minute
from Metropolis to my book.

00:08:19.770 --> 00:08:24.199
And the obvious question if you see a book
there and you see somebody who has spent their

00:08:24.199 --> 00:08:29.930
life being a newspaper reporter and written
books about serious topics like racial segregation

00:08:29.930 --> 00:08:34.329
is, why would you write a book about somebody
like Superman.

00:08:34.329 --> 00:08:37.560
And I wrote the book partly for a very serious
reason.

00:08:37.560 --> 00:08:42.909
I was fascinated, having written books, biographies
before on what I think of as American heroes

00:08:42.909 --> 00:08:48.819
and being in the process now of writing a
new biography on my hero growing up, who was

00:08:48.819 --> 00:08:50.389
a guy named Bobby Kennedy.

00:08:50.389 --> 00:08:55.749
I was intrigued why America embraced the heroes
we do.

00:08:55.749 --> 00:09:02.339
What is it that the hero tells us about them
and about ourselves that we think certain

00:09:02.339 --> 00:09:03.420
people are heroes?

00:09:03.420 --> 00:09:10.670
Today, in today's world politicians last as
heroes for about 15 seconds.

00:09:10.670 --> 00:09:15.579
When Barack Obama ran for senator from Illinois,
he posed next to this Superman statue in what

00:09:15.579 --> 00:09:22.089
may be the most famous picture on the internet
of Barack Obama.

00:09:22.089 --> 00:09:24.319
If you Google, of course Google, the, if you
Google Barack Obama and Superman you will

00:09:24.319 --> 00:09:29.689
see a picture of him and the statue that became
widely circulated during his 2008 campaigning

00:09:29.689 --> 00:09:30.779
for president.

00:09:30.779 --> 00:09:37.870
But from Barack Obama to Michael Jordan to
whomever are our hero is today, they don't

00:09:37.870 --> 00:09:39.170
seem to last long.

00:09:39.170 --> 00:09:46.130
And Superman has lasted for 74 years and so
I thought a good way to look at heroes was

00:09:46.130 --> 00:09:53.759
to look at the guy who maybe the longest,
you see it there, OK great, look at the longest

00:09:53.759 --> 00:09:56.480
lasting hero of the last century who is Superman.

00:09:56.480 --> 00:09:59.740
So that was a serious reason for writing this
book.

00:09:59.740 --> 00:10:04.070
The real reason, the other and maybe more
important reason was I wanted to be ten years

00:10:04.070 --> 00:10:05.410
old again.

00:10:05.410 --> 00:10:10.860
And for the last year, for the last two years,
be able to call Superman my work, let me be

00:10:10.860 --> 00:10:13.250
ten years old.

00:10:13.250 --> 00:10:18.420
What I want to do, anybody here grow up as
a Superman fan?

00:10:18.420 --> 00:10:22.730
Sort of sort of, yeah, metza metz, no, nobody.

00:10:22.730 --> 00:10:28.709
Well the, so I also wanted to see what there
was to find out about Superman, the serious

00:10:28.709 --> 00:10:32.959
stuff about the hero part, but also whether
there were new things that I could find out

00:10:32.959 --> 00:10:35.059
that even the most avid Superman fan wouldn't
know.

00:10:35.059 --> 00:10:38.559
And I just came back from a place called Comic-Con.

00:10:38.559 --> 00:10:40.740
Anybody know what Comic-Con is?

00:10:40.740 --> 00:10:46.990
Comic-Con is from San Diego, where every year
150,000 very crazy people [laughter] go to

00:10:46.990 --> 00:10:47.990
San Diego.

00:10:47.990 --> 00:10:52.519
And the only way I can describe to anybody
who hasn't been to Comic-Con what it's like

00:10:52.519 --> 00:10:59.959
is, if you have ever been in Times Square
on New Years Eve and you see a million people

00:10:59.959 --> 00:11:05.290
packed sort of cheek by jowl and yet they
all look like they're having fun.

00:11:05.290 --> 00:11:09.249
They, they for anybody who is claustrophobic,
you'd think it would be a nightmare, but people

00:11:09.249 --> 00:11:10.860
are having fun.

00:11:10.860 --> 00:11:16.610
150,000 fans at Comic-Con for an entire four
days look like they are having a blast.

00:11:16.610 --> 00:11:23.379
80% of them are dressed up in some crazy costume
and they are in a San Diego summer walking

00:11:23.379 --> 00:11:28.309
around with incredible stuff on them, must
make them feel like it's 200 degrees, but

00:11:28.309 --> 00:11:29.559
they are having a blast.

00:11:29.559 --> 00:11:30.559
And I wanted to be able to tell them, even
the craziest Superman fans, things that the

00:11:30.559 --> 00:11:31.559
character that they didn't know.

00:11:31.559 --> 00:11:38.559
And I want to just tell you a couple of those
things I found out about Superman.

00:11:38.559 --> 00:11:45.300
One is, his creator, do we know who created
Superman, who wrote the first Superman story?

00:11:45.300 --> 00:11:46.500
&gt;&gt; Male #1: Siegel?

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:49.519
[inaudible]
&gt;&gt; Larry: Jerry Siegel, Jerry Siegel, so we've

00:11:49.519 --> 00:11:52.870
speculated for 74 years what Jerry Siegel
was thinking.

00:11:52.870 --> 00:11:57.589
he would give short interviews but in the
process of writing this book I came across

00:11:57.589 --> 00:12:03.709
Jerry Siegel's unpublished hundred page memoir
where he told us precisely what he was thinking,

00:12:03.709 --> 00:12:05.670
why he created the character.

00:12:05.670 --> 00:12:10.739
And the reason he created the character is
because Jerry Siegel when he was growing up

00:12:10.739 --> 00:12:18.839
in a section of Cleveland, Ohio called Glenville,
a section that was very poor and 95% Jewish.

00:12:18.839 --> 00:12:24.690
Jerry Siegel was a little bit too short and
little bit too round and wore glasses that

00:12:24.690 --> 00:12:28.809
were a little bit too thick and everyday when
he would go to school, particularly when he

00:12:28.809 --> 00:12:34.089
would go out on the playground at recess time,
kids would taunt him.

00:12:34.089 --> 00:12:38.449
He was, in the classic sense, a kid who was
bullied.

00:12:38.449 --> 00:12:42.999
And they'd come up to him and they'd say "Siegel
Siegel, birds of an eagle."

00:12:42.999 --> 00:12:48.829
Now I have no idea what that means, other
than that if you are a 15 year old or a 12

00:12:48.829 --> 00:12:52.959
year old kid, you'd wish you could fly away,
because everybody's watching, particularly

00:12:52.959 --> 00:12:57.459
all the girls that were watching him and he
was incredibly embarrassed.

00:12:57.459 --> 00:13:03.540
And so every night when he would go to bed
he would take a pad of paper and a pencil

00:13:03.540 --> 00:13:09.810
and he would draw a world and imagine a world
that would take him away from his real world

00:13:09.810 --> 00:13:10.810
of being bullied.

00:13:10.810 --> 00:13:17.459
And he created a character to start with that
was called The Super hyphen Man.

00:13:17.459 --> 00:13:23.470
And this was a character who was a really
bad guy who wanted to take over the world

00:13:23.470 --> 00:13:29.489
the way that Jerry wished that he could've
done and basically, you know, pummel all of

00:13:29.489 --> 00:13:33.679
his kids who were bullying him everyday and
that was sort of every kid's reaction, normal

00:13:33.679 --> 00:13:38.269
reaction, that you want to be stronger than
everybody else and do them harm if that's

00:13:38.269 --> 00:13:42.209
what it takes to sort of to get free of that
bullying.

00:13:42.209 --> 00:13:48.129
And that was the way the character looked
until at age 17, something traumatic happened

00:13:48.129 --> 00:13:49.149
to Jerry Siegel.

00:13:49.149 --> 00:13:55.879
His dad owned a used clothing store in a part
of Cleveland that was sort of a rough neighborhood.

00:13:55.879 --> 00:14:02.019
And one day three guys come into that clothing
store and they try on a suit and they walk

00:14:02.019 --> 00:14:03.290
out without paying.

00:14:03.290 --> 00:14:11.170
And Michael Siegel starts to go after them
and, on the spot, he has a massive heart attack

00:14:11.170 --> 00:14:13.259
and he basically drops dead.

00:14:13.259 --> 00:14:20.420
And at age 17 this kid, Jerry, who is the
youngest of six siblings of Lithuanian Jewish

00:14:20.420 --> 00:14:23.699
immigrant parents, is suddenly bereft.

00:14:23.699 --> 00:14:27.119
He has lost his dad, he has lost his hero.

00:14:27.119 --> 00:14:32.199
And shortly after that, when he goes to bed
at night with his pad of paper and his pencil,

00:14:32.199 --> 00:14:34.699
the character Superman is transformed.

00:14:34.699 --> 00:14:41.870
He drops the 'the', he drops the hyphen and
he drops the bad guy act.

00:14:41.870 --> 00:14:45.910
And in this story that Jerry Siegel writes,
the first story he writes in this new Superman

00:14:45.910 --> 00:14:52.439
character, he runs over the next morning after
finishing his story to his buddy and his neighbor

00:14:52.439 --> 00:14:54.320
Joe Shuster's home.

00:14:54.320 --> 00:14:57.800
And Joe Shuster is an artist teenage nerd.

00:14:57.800 --> 00:15:05.480
And Joe Shuster in his first rendition of
the Superman character draws a guy who is

00:15:05.480 --> 00:15:12.970
speeding in to save a man who is being robbed
who looks suspiciously like Michael Siegel.

00:15:12.970 --> 00:15:18.029
So what Superman really is, from the very
beginning is a story of a little boy fighting

00:15:18.029 --> 00:15:21.739
back against a world that seems kind of cruel
to him.

00:15:21.739 --> 00:15:26.360
Only something magical happens that the moment
that Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster develop

00:15:26.360 --> 00:15:32.639
their character, America is at a moment when
it needs a hero maybe more than it ever has

00:15:32.639 --> 00:15:33.639
in its history.

00:15:33.639 --> 00:15:38.849
We are, in 1938 when the first Superman story
comes out, we're in the middle of what?

00:15:38.849 --> 00:15:39.849
&gt;&gt; Male #2: Depression.

00:15:39.849 --> 00:15:40.989
&gt;&gt; Larry: The Great Depression.

00:15:40.989 --> 00:15:47.089
We're now in the middle of a some other depression
but this was the Great Depression, the one

00:15:47.089 --> 00:15:48.889
that seemed to last forever.

00:15:48.889 --> 00:15:53.749
We're also on the eve of being dragged into
a war in Europe.

00:15:53.749 --> 00:15:57.549
And we're basically a country that's not quite
sure where we're going.

00:15:57.549 --> 00:16:04.290
And we need a hero and Jerry Shus, Joe Shuster
and Jerry Siegel give us a hero in a magical

00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:10.529
moment that guarantees that starting from
that very first issue in June 1938, basically

00:16:10.529 --> 00:16:14.660
every time Superman's on the cover of DC comics
he sold out.

00:16:14.660 --> 00:16:21.029
And he sold out in numbers in hundreds of
thousands and close to a million numbers that

00:16:21.029 --> 00:16:25.309
comic books have never seen happen, they were
a new medium and this was unheard of.

00:16:25.309 --> 00:16:30.389
So the first story I wanted to tell you about
Superman is, that it all starts like everything

00:16:30.389 --> 00:16:35.110
with really human scale story and in this
case a bullied boy named Jerry.

00:16:35.110 --> 00:16:38.540
The other story I want to tell you about Superman.

00:16:38.540 --> 00:16:42.350
Anybody have any idea what religion Superman
is?

00:16:42.350 --> 00:16:46.170
Why would Superman have a religion?

00:16:46.170 --> 00:16:48.059
How would we even know about his religion?

00:16:48.059 --> 00:16:52.339
Well, I want to tell you that every religion
out there has embraced Superman as theirs.

00:16:52.339 --> 00:16:55.399
Christians see Superman as the perfect Christ
story.

00:16:55.399 --> 00:17:00.930
God sends His only son to earth to show mankind
that it could better than it thought it could

00:17:00.930 --> 00:17:06.930
be, and to raise the standards and to raise
the hope of mankind.

00:17:06.930 --> 00:17:10.589
Buddhists see Superman as the perfect Zen
character.

00:17:10.589 --> 00:17:16.189
Who could be more Zen than Superman who knows
right from wrong and just doesn't even have

00:17:16.189 --> 00:17:18.549
to think about any of this?

00:17:18.549 --> 00:17:21.770
Atheists and agnostics see Superman as a secular
messiah.

00:17:21.770 --> 00:17:23.309
Who needs religion?

00:17:23.309 --> 00:17:26.150
Superman knows right from wrong and it's not
about religion.

00:17:26.150 --> 00:17:31.980
Well, I'm here to tell you what Superman's
real religion is and Superman is Jewish.

00:17:31.980 --> 00:17:34.909
And I want to tell you why I think Superman
is Jewish.

00:17:34.909 --> 00:17:38.080
Anybody know what Superman's name was when
he came down from Krypton?

00:17:38.080 --> 00:17:39.620
&gt;&gt; Group: Kal-El
&gt;&gt; Larry: Kal-El.

00:17:39.620 --> 00:17:41.149
Anybody speak Hebrew here?

00:17:41.149 --> 00:17:42.149
Little bit.

00:17:42.149 --> 00:17:43.460
What does El mean?

00:17:43.460 --> 00:17:45.520
Do you know what El means?

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:48.390
&gt;&gt; Male #3: God
&gt;&gt; Larry: El means God.

00:17:48.390 --> 00:17:53.340
Kal means, Kal-El suggests the vessel or voice
of God.

00:17:53.340 --> 00:17:54.340
Accidental?

00:17:54.340 --> 00:17:55.340
Maybe.

00:17:55.340 --> 00:17:56.550
I don't think anything is accidental.

00:17:56.550 --> 00:18:01.740
When you grow up in a world that's 95% Jewish
and all of this is part of what Jerry Siegel

00:18:01.740 --> 00:18:04.820
told us in his memoir that he was doing which
is writing about what he knows.

00:18:04.820 --> 00:18:05.820
I don't think it's an accident.

00:18:05.820 --> 00:18:12.510
But if that was an accident, as much as Superman
might look like the Christ story, there's

00:18:12.510 --> 00:18:16.410
a better story, there's an even more compelling
metaphor that I think Superman is playing

00:18:16.410 --> 00:18:17.410
out.

00:18:17.410 --> 00:18:25.059
And this is a story of parents trying to save
their child by floating him out to space to

00:18:25.059 --> 00:18:29.669
a river [audience member chuckles] and he's
adopted by two of the most extraordinary gentiles

00:18:29.669 --> 00:18:34.470
that the world has ever seen which are John
and Martha Kent in the middle of Kansas.

00:18:34.470 --> 00:18:40.960
And they raise the child as their own and
suddenly discover this child is really somebody

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:41.960
exceptional.

00:18:41.960 --> 00:18:46.529
Now if that's not the story of Moses in Exodus
then I don't know what the story of Exodus

00:18:46.529 --> 00:18:47.529
is.

00:18:47.529 --> 00:18:51.130
There are in my book, I go through 20 other
pieces of little hints that Jerry and Joe

00:18:51.130 --> 00:19:00.211
left us, but to me the most fun is any name
that ends in the word 'm-a-n', man, is one

00:19:00.211 --> 00:19:05.539
of two things: it is either a super hero or
a Jew or in this case both.

00:19:05.539 --> 00:19:10.880
So it's not Superman, its Superman.

00:19:10.880 --> 00:19:17.039
So one more thing I really want to tell you
here now which is the question that I started

00:19:17.039 --> 00:19:22.659
the whole book process with, which is what
is Superman, is there a serious story in Superman?

00:19:22.659 --> 00:19:28.080
Anybody who spends a year or two writing a
biography and any publisher who's going to

00:19:28.080 --> 00:19:33.289
publish a biography, a serious publisher like
Random House, publishes it only if the book

00:19:33.289 --> 00:19:38.779
is a lens into something bigger than just
the story of a comic book character.

00:19:38.779 --> 00:19:45.580
And to me I think there are two reasons that
we could learn as to why Superman has survived

00:19:45.580 --> 00:19:47.409
for nearly 75 years.

00:19:47.409 --> 00:19:50.820
Next summer, you will be bombarded with Superman
stuff.

00:19:50.820 --> 00:19:56.400
There will be a movie out and there will be
a million celebrations of Superman's seventy

00:19:56.400 --> 00:19:57.400
fifth birthday.

00:19:57.400 --> 00:20:00.919
And everybody will be asking, "How has he
managed to last for so long?

00:20:00.919 --> 00:20:03.399
When our heroes today disappear in 15 minutes?"

00:20:03.399 --> 00:20:08.082
And I think there are two reasons that he
has.

00:20:08.082 --> 00:20:13.710
One is that he has evolved more than the fruit
fly, that every generation has gotten a Superman

00:20:13.710 --> 00:20:17.940
that is specific to what their particular
needs and aspirations are.

00:20:17.940 --> 00:20:25.360
In the 1930s, we were a country, in the 1930s,
we were a country, we were a country on the

00:20:25.360 --> 00:20:30.130
eve of war in the middle of a depression and
we got a Superman who was the consummate New

00:20:30.130 --> 00:20:31.890
Deal liberal.

00:20:31.890 --> 00:20:37.940
He was going out trying to chase down slum
lords and wife beaters and he never told us

00:20:37.940 --> 00:20:43.100
how he voted but we all knew he voted for
Franklin Roosevelt and the whole idea of social

00:20:43.100 --> 00:20:44.429
change in America.

00:20:44.429 --> 00:20:46.279
Because that was what we needed then.

00:20:46.279 --> 00:20:51.440
In the 1940s, when we were going to war, we
need a different kind of hero.

00:20:51.440 --> 00:20:54.980
And Superman took us to war in a very interesting
way.

00:20:54.980 --> 00:20:59.429
You remember, anybody remember whether Superman
ever actually went to war?

00:20:59.429 --> 00:21:01.950
Well, DC comics was really worried about.

00:21:01.950 --> 00:21:07.789
They were worried that if they sent Superman
off to war, that people would say "He could

00:21:07.789 --> 00:21:09.059
win the war in 15 minutes.

00:21:09.059 --> 00:21:13.649
He'd just take over and he'd crush the Nazis
and he'd win the war."

00:21:13.649 --> 00:21:18.480
And that would be disparaging the efforts
of our real soldiers who were going over and

00:21:18.480 --> 00:21:20.770
being wounded and killed overseas.

00:21:20.770 --> 00:21:26.139
So what they did in a brilliant comic book
was, they had Clark Kent go in and do his

00:21:26.139 --> 00:21:31.539
induction exam and we all know that every
induction exam, you have to read an eye chart.

00:21:31.539 --> 00:21:35.860
And he was looking at the eye chart, only
instead of reading that eye chart, he was

00:21:35.860 --> 00:21:41.440
reading an eye chart two examining rooms in
because he had x-ray vision.

00:21:41.440 --> 00:21:44.880
[laughter] And he failed his eye test and
this was a particularly compelling explanation

00:21:44.880 --> 00:21:48.500
for Joe Shuster who had terrible eye sight
and who was drawing Superman.

00:21:48.500 --> 00:21:52.380
He failed his eye test and that meant that
he had to stay home.

00:21:52.380 --> 00:21:57.380
And what he ended up doing with Superman throughout
the war years, was he ended up chasing down

00:21:57.380 --> 00:22:02.600
saboteurs and protecting us on the home front
and for the government, anytime they did a

00:22:02.600 --> 00:22:08.070
war bond drive or were trying to collect metals
or newspapers or anything precious to the

00:22:08.070 --> 00:22:15.360
war effort, Superman was out there on their
posters as the centerpiece of their drive.

00:22:15.360 --> 00:22:21.139
Every ration kit that went overseas to one
of our troops included a comic book and most

00:22:21.139 --> 00:22:23.279
of the time it was a Superman comic book.

00:22:23.279 --> 00:22:28.980
So he was out there making soldiers feel like
there was still a little escape from their

00:22:28.980 --> 00:22:29.980
horrible world.

00:22:29.980 --> 00:22:34.539
And they could read about Superman, he was
making people at home feel patriotic in buying

00:22:34.539 --> 00:22:40.230
their war bonds and he was giving America
precisely the hero that we needed in the 1940s.

00:22:40.230 --> 00:22:42.769
In the 1950s what was our preoccupation?

00:22:42.769 --> 00:22:44.149
&gt;&gt; Male #4: Communism.

00:22:44.149 --> 00:22:45.149
&gt;&gt; Larry: Communism.

00:22:45.149 --> 00:22:46.450
The red menace.

00:22:46.450 --> 00:22:49.259
Superman was out there chasing down the red
menace.

00:22:49.259 --> 00:22:57.159
In the 1960s, when we were exploring all kinds
of new avenues, Superman, for part of that

00:22:57.159 --> 00:22:59.640
time, was consciously divorced from that.

00:22:59.640 --> 00:23:05.130
There was guy named Mort Weisinger who in
the 1960s created what were known as imaginary

00:23:05.130 --> 00:23:10.510
stories as if Superman in concept wasn't himself
an imaginary story.

00:23:10.510 --> 00:23:14.950
And Superman would get married, or he'd die,
or he'd do all these things and at the end

00:23:14.950 --> 00:23:16.970
of the comic book, they would say "Oh, by
the way, this was an imaginary story."

00:23:16.970 --> 00:23:17.970
And it probably didn't happen and next comic
book, he won't be married again.

00:23:17.970 --> 00:23:29.779
In the 1970s and 80s and 90s, he continued
to do that he continued to give us precisely

00:23:29.779 --> 00:23:30.810
what we needed for that era.

00:23:30.810 --> 00:23:38.669
So part of the reason I think he survived
forever, is that he evolved, he changed with

00:23:38.669 --> 00:23:39.669
our times.

00:23:39.669 --> 00:23:40.669
The other reasons is precisely the opposite.

00:23:40.669 --> 00:23:46.480
Is that the most important core elements of
Superman maintained themselves around all

00:23:46.480 --> 00:23:48.650
of this time, through all those changes.

00:23:48.650 --> 00:23:56.230
And that was most importantly the Dudley Do-Right
guy who knows exactly the difference between

00:23:56.230 --> 00:23:58.990
right and wrong and never wavers in his choice.

00:23:58.990 --> 00:24:03.100
The world had lots of dark heroes like Batman.

00:24:03.100 --> 00:24:10.100
The world had lots of fraught and anxious
heroes like Spiderman, but there was one guy

00:24:10.100 --> 00:24:15.340
who was always out there when we needed some
sense of right and wrong, Superman was out

00:24:15.340 --> 00:24:22.600
there as clunky as that might have seemed
it also to kids and their parents and their

00:24:22.600 --> 00:24:27.649
grandparents that seemed familiar enough,
that Superman was always there as the touchstone

00:24:27.649 --> 00:24:31.380
for a certain kind of righteous hero in America.

00:24:31.380 --> 00:24:37.120
And I think those two capacities put together
all but gave us a character that has survived

00:24:37.120 --> 00:24:43.440
for nearly 75 years and if the lawyers and
the heirs to Superman who are doing battle

00:24:43.440 --> 00:24:47.899
over his rights right now don't screw it up,
he'll be around for another 75 years.

00:24:47.899 --> 00:24:53.759
What I think I would like to do here is actually
stop and see if we wanted to questions, discussion

00:24:53.759 --> 00:24:54.759
or anything?

00:24:54.759 --> 00:24:55.759
Yeah?

00:24:55.759 --> 00:25:05.009
&gt;&gt; Male #5: So you mentioned that we're coming
up on the 75th anniversary, what was the timing

00:25:05.009 --> 00:25:11.520
of this book, why not wait a little longer
so you can really pick up on that [inaudible].

00:25:11.520 --> 00:25:13.600
&gt;&gt; Larry: For me the timing of it.

00:25:13.600 --> 00:25:15.309
Oh it was two things.

00:25:15.309 --> 00:25:20.540
One is, I'll be candid with you that the timing
was partly the movie was due out this summer

00:25:20.540 --> 00:25:30.000
and I thought it was really good timing to
have it just when the movie was coming out.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.580
Imagine if you had a history of Batman out
at this moment you would be there interviewed

00:25:32.580 --> 00:25:33.580
by a million people.

00:25:33.580 --> 00:25:37.150
Well, in fact it turned out to be kind of
brilliant timing accidental that this is the

00:25:37.150 --> 00:25:38.830
summer of the superhero in America.

00:25:38.830 --> 00:25:45.120
We had the Avengers, we had Batman, we had
Spiderman, and we even had an animated Superman

00:25:45.120 --> 00:25:46.720
called Superman versus the Elite.

00:25:46.720 --> 00:25:51.690
So the timing has been great and your dream
as an author, there are certain touchstones

00:25:51.690 --> 00:25:57.490
