00:30:26.419 --> 00:30:35.769
and Shuster, was something that was in here
[unintelligible], was like somebody that he

00:30:35.769 --> 00:30:41.370
talks to about
&gt;&gt; Larry: If you haven't, if you don't know

00:30:41.370 --> 00:30:48.400
who Michael Schiavone is, there is only one
thing you should know about Michael Schiavone,

00:30:48.400 --> 00:31:01.179
there's only one book, he's written a lot
of good books, but there's only one book that

00:31:01.179 --> 00:31:11.970
rises above everything and that's Kavalier
and Clay.

00:31:11.970 --> 00:31:14.630
And that is a book about two fictional comic
book creators.

00:31:14.630 --> 00:31:29.080
That as you say is really Jerry Siegel and
Joe Shuster and it is a book that is so good

00:31:29.080 --> 00:31:36.850
that the nicest thing I could ever say about
a book is when I got near the end, I would

00:31:36.850 --> 00:31:44.510
ration myself a certain number of pages to
read every night because I didn't want the

00:31:44.510 --> 00:31:48.340
book to end, it was really brilliant.

00:31:48.340 --> 00:32:03.730
And so my goal was to write a book a non-fiction
that drew on the same rich story he did in

00:32:03.730 --> 00:32:23.570
fiction and while they call these things on
the back of the book blurbs and the guy who

00:32:23.570 --> 00:32:30.140
was the executive producer of the big Batman
movies and taught the first course, ever,

00:32:30.140 --> 00:32:42.950
on comic books, said a nice thing which is
not true, but a nice thing, he said, "If you

00:32:42.950 --> 00:32:52.990
like reading the amazing adventures of Kavalier
and Clay, wait till you read Larry Tye's true

00:32:52.990 --> 00:32:55.519
story behind it all."

00:32:55.519 --> 00:33:03.279
That's sort of the dream kind of thing that
you want somebody, because this was the book

00:33:03.279 --> 00:33:05.070
that was really brilliant.

00:33:05.070 --> 00:33:12.639
But the great thing that I found out was that
the only thing better than writing brilliant

00:33:12.639 --> 00:33:19.999
fiction is to find a non-fiction story that
reads like fiction and Jerry and Joe's story

00:33:19.999 --> 00:33:26.889
and Superman's story, if you can't write a
good non-fiction book about that then shame

00:33:26.889 --> 00:33:32.510
on you because the story is incredibly rich,
it has 75 years in it.

00:33:32.510 --> 00:33:40.610
&gt;&gt; Male #8: So were you a Superman fan [inaudible]
&gt;&gt; Larry: So I grew up as a, so there are

00:33:40.610 --> 00:33:44.029
a million incarnations of Superman, there
are all the various incarnations in the comic

00:33:44.029 --> 00:33:48.950
books depending on who is writing it, or who
is drawing it.

00:33:48.950 --> 00:33:51.000
There are various TV shows.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:57.150
There are, you know, I didn't know until I
started writing this book, I'm embarrassed

00:33:57.150 --> 00:34:04.700
to say about this whole generation that had
grown up with Smallville as their version

00:34:04.700 --> 00:34:07.220
of who Superman was.

00:34:07.220 --> 00:34:19.860
And then the Superman coming of age story
that's made it through nine seasons of television.

00:34:19.860 --> 00:34:27.020
I grew up as a Superman fan starting with
the TV series and in the 1950s TV series,

00:34:27.020 --> 00:34:39.300
if you could believe that this was a Superman
that was played by a guy named George Reeves,

00:34:39.300 --> 00:34:44.000
who in his incarnation as Superman, looked
exactly like his incarnations of Clark Kent

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:45.920
minus the glasses.

00:34:45.920 --> 00:34:57.410
Who acted, who had no clue how to change his
persona, how to change his voice, his flying

00:34:57.410 --> 00:35:06.730
was jumping off a trampoline through a window
and then having a crane hold him up in the

00:35:06.730 --> 00:35:18.310
air and it looked about as much like flying
as if somebody held me up in the air and you

00:35:18.310 --> 00:35:26.120
whooshed by with a lot of fans blowing and
tried to make it look.

00:35:26.120 --> 00:35:33.320
And yet I believed he was Superman because
I wanted to believe, I wanted the character

00:35:33.320 --> 00:35:36.190
to be real and I was ten years old.

00:35:36.190 --> 00:35:46.070
And yes, I was a fan and I was a fan, I'm
saying, back in the days when Superman was

00:35:46.070 --> 00:35:52.990
so crude that if you were willing to buy into
it all you had a pretty good story.

00:35:52.990 --> 00:35:57.650
By the 1970s people who met with Christopher
Reeve in those Superman movies, by the 1970s

00:35:57.650 --> 00:36:01.660
their motto, their marketing line when they
were marketing those four Christopher Reeve

00:36:01.660 --> 00:36:04.590
movies was, "You will believe a man can fly."

00:36:04.590 --> 00:36:06.070
And you did believe it.

00:36:06.070 --> 00:36:12.960
And by the time we get to the 2013 Man of
Steel story, in the short 30 second blurb

00:36:12.960 --> 00:36:21.430
that we saw in the Batman movie, it looked
like he was flying to meet him, it was just

00:36:21.430 --> 00:36:22.430
really now you can do a million things.

00:36:22.430 --> 00:36:27.600
But in those early days it was the story that
kept us riveted because all the technology

00:36:27.600 --> 00:36:28.600
looked so miserable.

